messages.content:
CLUSTER:
[
 {
  "riskId": "risk.ledger-self-audit.oem-cell-double-squeeze-foreclosure",
  "title": "The 0.22 OEM/integrator cell is squeezed from both sides — branded incumbents win the spec, Taiwanese ODMs win the white-label — leaving no seat for a CE entrant",
  "narrative": "cust.oem carries 0.22 of the buyer mix with no derivation, no evidence rows, and needs-source maturity — yet it silently props up 22% of the SAM as a fallback channel if large operators prove hard. The corpus says the cell is real but not contestable: every integrator case study found shows integrators selecting branded incumbents on certification, DCIM compatibility and support, while the actual white-label volume is already served by established OEM/ODM specialists (Digipower-class manufacturers) competing on Asian cost structures. A new CE industrial entrant is neither the trusted brand nor the cost-floor ODM. This is not a smaller cell — it is a cell that exists for other players, which is why the correct model operation is exclusion, not shrinkage.",
  "mechanism": [
   {
    "step": "trigger",
    "text": "Rack integrators and distributors source PDUs either as branded components (feature/cert/DCIM-driven) or as private-label from dedicated ODM houses whose entire business is OEM/ODM design at scale",
    "refs": [
     "digest:cust-mix#c13",
     "digest:cust-mix#c14"
    ]
   },
   {
    "step": "propagation",
    "text": "A pre-launch CE entrant fails both selection filters simultaneously: no installed-base/DCIM ecosystem to win the branded path, no volume cost position to win the white-label path — and no source quantifies any historical case of a new regional entrant capturing integrator share",
    "refs": [
     "digest:cust-mix#c14",
     "ledger:cust.oem"
    ]
   },
   {
    "step": "model-impact",
    "text": "The 0.22 cell should be treated as foreclosed for the Year-1 horizon; SAM and the YAM pipeline built on four contestable channels actually rest on at most three, concentrating execution risk on the already-fragile large-operator cell",
    "refs": [
     "ledger:cust.oem",
     "ledger:cust.operator-large",
     "ledger:obtainableFactor"
    ]
   }
  ],
  "indicators": [
   {
    "signal": "Brand composition of PDUs in CE integrator rack-build catalogs and reference designs",
    "where": "Rittal/nVent/regional integrator configurators and partner catalogs; Vertiv and Legrand partner-program case studies",
    "threshold": "Zero non-top-5 PDU brands appearing in new integrator reference builds over two quarters",
    "updates": "increases"
   },
   {
    "signal": "ODM expansion into Europe (local stock, CE/TÜV-certified white-label lines)",
    "where": "Digipower and peer ODM product/price lists; distributor line-card announcements (e.g., master distributors adding Asian PDU lines)",
    "threshold": "≥1 major CE distributor adding an ODM white-label PDU line",
    "updates": "increases"
   }
  ],
  "judgeTotal": 16
 },
 {
  "riskId": "risk.competitive-foreclosure.oem-cell-two-sided-squeeze",
  "title": "The OEM/integrator cell is squeezed shut from both sides: brand-spec deals go to incumbent ecosystems, white-label seats go to scale ODMs",
  "narrative": "The 0.22 OEM/integrator cell looks like the natural entry channel for an industrial entrant — and superficially the evidence agrees, because BOTH routes into it are documented: integrators buy branded PDUs, and buyer's guides advertise OEM/private-label options. The trap is that each route is closed for a different reason. Every integrator case study found shows selection of branded incumbents on certification, DCIM compatibility and support ecosystems — assets a Year-1 entrant does not have. The white-label seats, meanwhile, are held by Asian ODMs (the Digipower pattern) competing on a manufacturing cost curve a Central European industrial entrant cannot match. The cell's 0.22 value is an unsourced internal estimate with an addressability premise no source supports; for this venture the genuinely open fraction may be a third of the modeled cell.",
  "mechanism": [
   {
    "step": "trigger",
    "text": "Rack integrators select PDU brands on features, certification and DCIM-ecosystem compatibility — the documented integrator behavior favors incumbents whose monitoring stacks are already deployed — while the private-label demand that does exist is served by dedicated OEM/ODM manufacturers with global scale",
    "refs": [
     "digest:cust-mix#c14",
     "digest:cust-mix#c13",
     "ledger:cust.oem"
    ]
   },
   {
    "step": "propagation",
    "text": "An industrial entrant sits in the dead zone between the two: no installed DCIM/support ecosystem to win brand-spec designs (those accrue to the Legrand/Raritan/Server Technology axis and the top-5 vendor set) and no ODM cost position to win price-spec white-label seats",
    "refs": [
     "digest:cr3-vendors#c4",
     "digest:cr3-vendors#c1",
     "profile:Company"
    ]
   },
   {
    "step": "model-impact",
    "text": "Addressable share of cust.oem falls from 0.22 to ~0.08 (the fraction of integrator demand that is regional, spec-flexible, and not price-anchored to ODM quotes); the funnel's channel mix shifts further onto cells that are themselves contested",
    "refs": [
     "ledger:cust.oem",
     "ledger:cust.operator-large"
    ]
   }
  ],
  "indicators": [
   {
    "signal": "PDU brands named in European integrator/turnkey rack case studies and reference designs",
    "where": "Vertiv, Legrand, Rittal and Schleifenbauer project case-study pages; DataCenterDynamics build coverage",
    "threshold": "≥3 consecutive quarters of new CE integrator projects specifying only incumbent-brand PDUs",
    "updates": "increases"
   },
   {
    "signal": "ODM intelligent-PDU pricing and OEM-program activity",
    "where": "Digipower and comparable ODM price lists / OEM program pages; Computex and Data Centre World exhibitor announcements",
    "threshold": "ODM per-outlet-managed PDU quotes ≥30% below the entrant's achievable unit cost",
    "updates": "increases"
   }
  ],
  "judgeTotal": 17
 },
 {
  "riskId": "risk.base-rate-analogy.channel-calendar-lockout",
  "title": "Distributor line-cards and integrator qualification run on annual calendars the 12-month plan cannot intersect",
  "narrative": "35% of the modeled funnel flows through OEM/integrator (0.22) and distributor (0.13) cells — both admitted internal estimates with zero evidence attached. The reference class says both channels have a calendar: distributor line-card reviews are annual events requiring certifications, stock commitments and demand proof in hand; integrators demonstrably select branded incumbents on certification, DCIM compatibility and support (every case study found — Vertiv/Greenergy, Legrand/MIND Park — shows brand selection, none shows a new entrant winning a slot). A pre-launch vendor with no certs on day 0 misses the current listing cycle entirely and enters the next one as an unproven applicant. Within the YAM window these two cells are not small — they are closed, and the model treats 'closed this year' as indistinguishable from 'open at 35%'.",
  "mechanism": [
   {
    "step": "trigger",
    "text": "Distributor line-card onboarding is an annual-cycle gate requiring completed certifications and reference installs at application time — assets a pre-launch entrant does not possess in month 1 and cannot assemble before the cycle closes",
    "refs": [
     "ledger:cust.distributor",
     "profile:Stage",
     "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c13"
    ]
   },
   {
    "step": "propagation",
    "text": "The parallel OEM/integrator path is gated the same way but on brand: integrators select PDU suppliers on certification, DCIM compatibility and support track record, a pattern consistent across the corpus's integrator case studies and the incumbent vendor sets that dominate every published landscape",
    "refs": [
     "ledger:cust.oem",
     "digest:cr3-vendors#c4",
     "digest:cr3-vendors#c7"
    ]
   },
   {
    "step": "model-impact",
    "text": "cust.oem (0.22) and cust.distributor (0.13) together carry 35% of the funnel into SAM, but within the first 12 months both cells are calendar-foreclosed; the SAM the Year-1 obtainable percentage is applied to is materially smaller than modeled",
    "refs": [
     "ledger:cust.oem",
     "ledger:cust.distributor"
    ]
   }
  ],
  "indicators": [
   {
    "signal": "Line-card additions in rack-power categories at CE electrical/IT distributors",
    "where": "Rexel, Sonepar, Also/Ingram product-catalog update announcements and new-vendor press releases",
    "threshold": "Zero new rack-PDU vendors added in the trailing two quarters signals a hard-gated cycle",
    "updates": "increases"
   },
   {
    "signal": "Integrator RFI/qualification requirements for PDU suppliers",
    "where": "Vendor-qualification questionnaires from CE rack integrators and modular-DC builders (e.g., responses to the venture's own outreach, logged monthly)",
    "threshold": "Certification-complete and ≥2 reference installs required at application in >75% of responses",
    "updates": "increases"
   }
  ],
  "judgeTotal": 16
 },
 {
  "riskId": "risk.structure-independence.framework-foreclosure-large-operator-cell",
  "title": "Global framework agreements dissolve the 'large operator direct' cell the venture plans to enter first",
  "narrative": "The funnel counts 40% of PDU spend as 'large operators' — the venture's declared first buyer. But the number is a capacity-share proxy, not a channel reality. The documented procurement pattern for exactly these buyers is HQ-level global frameworks and integrator bundles: pan-European colos and hyperscalers sign multi-year power-chain packages with Schneider/Vertiv-class suppliers or take PDUs embedded in OEM/ODM rack builds. A regional entrant never sees an RFP for that spend. The cell exists as consumption; it barely exists as a contestable transaction. The independence assumption geography × segment × buyer hides that the biggest buyer cell and the least reachable procurement route are the same cell.",
  "mechanism": [
   {
    "step": "trigger",
    "text": "Large operators consolidate rack-power procurement into global frameworks and integrated OEM/ODM packages: Vertiv's named major customers span Equinix and global telecoms, PDU vendors explicitly market OEM/private-label channels, and ODMs like Digipower supply operators via white-label design programs",
    "refs": [
     "digest:cust-mix#c12",
     "digest:cust-mix#c13",
     "digest:cust-mix#c14"
    ]
   },
   {
    "step": "propagation",
    "text": "The 0.40 cell was derived from 'hyperscale+colo ≈ 62% of capacity and large operators buy direct' — a consumption share, not a channel split; the only attached datapoint (30% of one supplier's orders) measures DC exposure, not who signs the PO. Spend transacted under frameworks negotiated outside CE is recorded in this cell but is foreclosed to a pre-launch regional entrant",
    "refs": [
     "ledger:cust.operator-large",
     "digest:cust-mix#c0"
    ]
   },
   {
    "step": "model-impact",
    "text": "cust.operator-large 0.40 overstates the discrete-buyer share of PDU spend; the funnel keeps 40% of TAM inside the venture's first channel while the real contestable route runs through OEM/integrator packages — a different sell with different economics",
    "refs": [
     "ledger:cust.operator-large",
     "ledger:cust.oem",
     "profile:Who is the primary buyer you'll sell through first?"
    ]
   }
  ],
  "indicators": [
   {
    "signal": "New pan-European power-chain framework agreements covering rack power announced by Equinix, Digital Realty, Vantage or NTT",
    "where": "Operator procurement press releases and capital-markets-day supplier disclosures",
    "threshold": "≥1 additional multi-year framework explicitly including rack PDUs",
    "updates": "increases"
   },
   {
    "signal": "Incumbents' revenue mix shifting from discrete products to 'integrated solutions' in DC segment commentary",
    "where": "Schneider Electric and Vertiv quarterly earnings calls, DC segment discussion",
    "threshold": "Solutions/bundled share of DC revenue growing while standalone product lines flatten",
    "updates": "increases"
   }
  ],
  "judgeTotal": 17
 }
]

Every riskId must appear in exactly one group (as keepId or inside absorbs).
Emit JSON: { rationale, groups: [{keepId, absorbs: [true-duplicate riskIds, [] if none], foldedIndicators: []}] }
